    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-02-02T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-02-02T14:00:00-05:00" n="389"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d389">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">632.6231/290: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janerio</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-02T16:00:00-03:00"
                            >February 2, 1938—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 2—2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>27. My 26, February 2, 3 p.m. Aranha is still insisting that it is more important
                    to control the exchange value of the compensation mark (my telegram No. 18,
                    January 27, 4 p.m.<note n="72" xml:id="d389fn72">Not printed.</note>) than it is
                    to attempt to prevent subsidies. I am endeavoring to persuade him of the error
                    of this.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
